# Final-report rule

When work is finished, produce exactly one complete, self-contained final message.

Assume the user will see only that final message and none of intermediate terminal output, file writes, progress notes, or earlier chat messages.

The final message must:

- contain the complete outcome
- state what was changed
- state what succeeded and failed
- include all important metrics and process states
- include exact commands or paths needed for manual action
- explain any remaining blocker
- never require the reader to open a JSON file or read a log to understand the result
- never say only "see report file" or "details above"
- not split the final report across several messages
- not place tool output, file-reading commentary, or partial findings between sections of the final report

Machine-readable logs and JSON files may be written internally, but summarize all relevant contents in the single final user-facing message.

Use this structure:

```text
FINAL STATUS: SUCCESS | PARTIAL SUCCESS | BLOCKED

Summary
What changed
Current live processes
Validation results
Generation/import status
Training/cache status
Failures or risks
Manual action required
Exact recovery/stop commands
```
